<font color="#FF0000">PROFESSOR  ON  TARGET</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jul  5 13:19:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Your valid views substantiates the need for careful and well thought out presentations which are tailored to the time allowed.  Aimless wanderings through this serious topic, conveyed by questionable war stories which sometimes focus more on self edification than education is not what young people need.<br>
Certainly, there is merit to be found in hearing first hand accounts from combat veterans.  Sensationalism can thwart boredom and help provide that efficacy of learning as suggested by Piaget.  Conversely, sensationalism can border on the inappropriate and return to haunt the host school.  The quagmire which lies ahead is the argument of what is and is not appropriate...  and let us not forget &quot;freedom of speech.&quot;  Some parents use foul language in the presence of children and other do not.  In a politically correct (I hate that term) world there are parameters that are subscribed to by those, without identities and a base of experience, who would control everyones' thoughts.<br>
I commend you in your efforts. Hopefully, we will gain more time in the classroom. I thank you for your past and present service to our country.  Welcome home!
<p><code>-- eramon@edumaster.net  (Edward Ramon) </code><p>


